    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2806483076" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2806483076" />
    <a title="The Usual" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/56007684-the-usual"><img alt="The Usual" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2806483076?book_show_action=true">May 24, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="The Usual" class="user" itemprop="url" name="The Usual" href="/user/show/56007684-the-usual">The Usual</a>
      </span>

          added it


          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/678042.Extraordinary_Popular_Delusions_and_the_Madness_of_Crowds">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2806483076" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17427634534435597505">The great strength - and weakness- of this book is that it was written by a nineteenth century journalist. It would be a very different thing had the author been a twenty-first century social scientist. It is best, then, to think of The Madness of Crowds as a catalogue of bizarre human behaviour, rather then a piece of popular science writing. Mackay wasn&apos;t trying to write about mass psychology or economics, after all. He was trying entertain his audience and to demonstrate, as effectively as po</span>
  <span id="freeText17427634534435597505" style="display:none">The great strength - and weakness- of this book is that it was written by a nineteenth century journalist. It would be a very different thing had the author been a twenty-first century social scientist. It is best, then, to think of The Madness of Crowds as a catalogue of bizarre human behaviour, rather then a piece of popular science writing. Mackay wasn't trying to write about mass psychology or economics, after all. He was trying entertain his audience and to demonstrate, as effectively as possible, one simple thing: that humans, as a species are quite incurably insane. Well, yes, we are! It doesn't matter whether we're burning witches, fighting holy wars, or flinging dairy-products at politicians*, we are a ridiculous species. We get wound up over such ridiculous things, and perform such ridiculous acts for such ridiculous reasons that you have to wonder why, if there is a God, the world contains so many sharp objects and so few padded surfaces... <br /><br />Which is to digress... <br /><br />Mackay, then, is quite long-winded, but that lends a certain gravity to his writing, and civilises his sarcasm (oh, the sarcasm!). He's too fond of a good story to be a good historian, but then, he's too fond of a good story not to tell 'em. He's delighted with his own opinions, which means he's far from unbiased, but expresses them well. However... <br /><br />Well, I'm glad I don't star-rate non-fiction, because this would be a bit of a puzzler. To stick a single number on a piece of non-fiction you really need to adopt the Janus-headed attitude of: was this engaging and entertaining? and: Is it actually true? It's quite hard to balance the one against the other. The Madness of Crowds is entertaining, yes: more so, perhaps in the famous first three chapters than for the rest of the book. It's great fun to watch Mackay be incredibly rude about people in that terribly civilized nineteenth-century way of his, and it's full of all sorts of delightful bits and bobs drawn from various sources. On the other hand: reliable? I rather doubt it. I think that at the very least he exaggerates and goes out looking for extreme examples. He's trying to entertain rather than necessarily to inform. <br />Those first three chapters are rather splendid, transforming the story of three market bubbles (the South Sea Company, the Mississippi Scheme and the Tulip Mania) into moral fables about greed and the superiority of British democracy over continental despotism. It lends a structure to what would otherwise be a collection of anecdotes and stock-market figures. The rest of the book takes a much more scattergun approach, and should probably be consumed piecemeal. <br /><br />I know the above doesn't quite hang together, but then neither does Mackay. <br /><br />So: if you want to be entertained, and confirmed in the Cheshire Cat's Credo, then by all means read it; if you want a textbook on economic behaviour then read one of those instead. <br />Done. <br /><br />* For the record, I don't approve of any of these things, not least because, some days, there isn't enough yogurt in the world. </span>
  <a data-text-id="17427634534435597505" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


